***** WIP Cleanups
******* DONE Some docstrings talk of EXPRESSIONS, some of FORMS.
******* DONE "Yields" vs "returns" a value.
******* DONE Restricts vs constrains.
        Public docstrings normalised to "constrain"; "restrict-X!"
        function names retained as internal API.
******* DONE Don't talk about noticers: they're an implementation detail.
        Noticer mentions removed from public docstrings (integerpv,
        rationalpv, ratiopv, floatpv, realpv, numberpv, memberv, notv,
        andv, orv, equalv, =v, <v, /=v, known?, assert!, decide).
        Bidirectional propagation now described as "mutually
        constrained" without exposing the noticer mechanism.
***** DONE Simplify the language in the constraint section.
      Constraint-section docstrings condensed: redundant per-direction
      noticer paragraphs replaced with concise "mutually constrained"
      statements. Manual texinfo prose was already clean.
* TODO Port LOCAL-OUTPUT to SLIME.
    iscream.el targets ILisp/bridge.el (abandoned ~2005). SLIME already
    handles Y-OR-N-P natively, and EMACS-EVAL is redundant with
    SWANK:EVAL-IN-EMACS. Only LOCAL-OUTPUT (backtrack-aware Emacs buffer
    output) is worth porting: write a screamer-slime.el using
    SWANK:EVAL-IN-EMACS for push-end-marker/pop-end-marker, and gate the
    macro on swank presence. iscream.el and the *iscream?* path can be
    dropped at that point.
* DONE Rewrite dynamic-extent continuations using FLET
    POSSIBLY-BETA-REDUCE-FUNCALL emits FLET for magic-cont/null-types
    sites and aliases the original cvar via LET to #'helper, enabling
    stack-allocation of continuation closures. *dynamic-extent?*
    removed: optimisation is now unconditional.
* DONE Dynamic-extent in CPS-CONVERT-TAGBODY.
    LABELS-bound continuations declared (dynamic-extent ...).
* WIP Split the system into logical pieces.
    Most of the DEFUN-COMPILE-TIME functions should probably go
    to a file of their own, loaded before the main screamer code
    is compiled.
* TODO Cleanups
*** DONE #:DUMMY-N gensyms used all over the place
    Renamed by role across CPS sites: OLD-/NEW- (trail save vs new
    value), TEST- (IF antecedent), LET-VALUE- (LET binding),
    MV- (multi-value &rest list), FN-VALUE- (multiple-value-call
    function), ARG- (call argument), IGNORED- (discarded args).
*** DONE DEFMACRO-COMPILE-TIME
      Check if Allegro still needs this.
      Used across all 4 supported impls (SBCL, CCL, LispWorks, Allegro).
*** DONE primordial.lisp has some commented-out tests using LOOP
    Apparently LOCAL and LOOP interactions depend on the specific
    expansion of loop. :/ If nothing else, documentation should
    mention this. An alternative would be to provide our own
    implemntation of LOOP that is well-behaved when it comes to LOCAL.
    test7 / test8 reactivated; the walker now dispatches LOOP on
    determinism (LABELS-recursive rewrite for nondet, host
    macroexpansion for det, with MACROLET/SYMBOL-MACROLET support).
*** TODO review the remaining limitations listed in the old source, and put the in the manual
     1. Does not handle SETF methods with multiple values for LOCAL
        SETF.
     2. If you do a (SETF (SYMBOL-FUNCTION 'FOO) ...) to a nondeterministic
	function you will lose when you attempt to evaluate (FOO ...).
     3. If you do a (SETF (SYMBOL-FUNCTION 'FOO) ...) to a deterministic
	function when FOO was previously defined as a nondeterministic
	function you will lose when you attempt to evaluate (FOO ...).
     4. DONE: FLET and LABELS now supported via cps-convert-flet/labels +
        *lexical-function-records*. Bindings are lexically scoped; calls to
        labels-bound nondet names dispatch through their CPS form.
     5. There is no way to force Screamer into compiling a deterministic
	function as a nondeterministic one. A wizard might want to do this to
	take advantage of the fact that a LOCAL SETF/SETQ in a nondeterministic
	function does not cons up closures.
* Bugs
*** TODO LOCAL only reliable with explicit SETF/SETQ:
    If (INCF (FOO)) expands into a form that does SET-FOO instead of
    (SETF (FOO) ...) form, the code walker will not know about the
    side-effect.

    Options:
    - Implement SCREAMER:INCF, etc.
    - Wrap all non-SETF/SETQ forms in GLOBAL, so that those side-effects are never undone.
    - Leave it as-is.
* Old "Bugs to fix" list from screamer.lisp
  These haven't been verified or anything, just moved here.
*** TODO Deterministic/nondeterministic LOCAL SETF/SETQ undone out of order.
    No regression test or repro available; bug is unverified in 4.0.1.
    Needs a deliberate failing example before acting.
*** TODO Changing determinism status
    can cause code from a different file to be included causing wierd behavior.
*** TODO May loop when expressions contain circular lists.
    Confirmed still present in 4.0.1: occurs-in?, attach-noticer!-internal,
    attach-dependencies!-internal carry "Will loop if X is circular" notes.
    apply-substitution/contains-variables? have no cycle guard either.
    Preserved behaviour from upstream; circular Screamer expressions are
    rare in practice.
*** DONE APPLY-NONDETERMINISTIC conses.
    Reduced via (apply #'apply ...) flattening in
    apply-nondeterministic-nondeterministic.
